   102	- `effect`, `batch`, `untracked`, and `configure` form the non-React API.
   103	  `batch` delays core-effect flushing only; it never delays watcher delivery.
   104	  Synchronous effect flushing is a documented configuration for benchmark
   105	  adapters.
   106	- Writes inside ordinary computeds are accepted when the graph remains
   107	  acyclic. `configure({forbidWritesInComputeds:true})` rejects them. Every
   108	  render-world evaluation rejects writes. Signal access from an updater or a
   109	  replayed reducer callback throws in all builds.
   110	- React-coupled update storms use React's own render/update-depth limits
   111	  because delivery is a real `setState`. Signal-only evaluation/write cycles
   112	  use the engine's generation-checked cycle and flush-depth limits.
   113	
   114	Errors and suspensions are reference-stable sentinel values until the getter
   115	boundary rethrows them. Graph tracking always closes in `finally`, so a throw
   116	cannot leave half-installed edges.
   117	
   118	### 1.2 React API
   119	
   120	`cosignal/react` exports `useSignal`, `useAtom`, `useReducerAtom`,
   121	`useComputed(fn,deps,opts?)`, and `useSignalEffect(fn,deps?)`. Hook computeds
   122	close over props/state and auto-track signal reads. It also exports
   123	`startSignalTransition(fn(scope))`; `scope` has only `set` and `dispatch`.
   124	Ordinary `startTransition` and `useTransition` require no provider. Importing
   125	the binding feature-detects fork protocol v4 and fails loudly on stock or
   126	version-skewed React.
   127	
   128	`useSignalEffect` reads only committed-for-root state. Its function/deps
   129	identity is owned by React's native effect re-fire; it does not use staged
   130	evaluator publication. Core `effect()` instead observes K0 NEWEST and may run
   131	before React commits.
   132	
   133	### 1.3 Multi-root scope
   134	
   135	Full spanning batches are supported. Roots may commit at different times, but
   136	each root's later renders and effects include every prefix already committed
   137	on that root. A token retires globally exactly once after its React work and
   138	parked action have closed.
   139	
   140	A hook-stageable signal node has one owning hook/root, already identified by
   141	its F9 publication record. Subscribing that node from another root throws at
   142	subscription time. This detectable restriction avoids inventing per-root
   143	evaluator publication: share ordinary atoms, computeds, and constructor
   144	ReducerAtoms across roots; create a separate `useComputed` or
   145	`useReducerAtom` per root. Portals remain in their parent root and are legal.
   146	
   147	### 1.4 SSR and hydration
   148	
   149	SSR runs DIRECT and serializes atom ids, generations, and values. Hydration
   150	restores K0 before the React bridge activates LOGGED. No receipt exists at the
   151	switch, so every restored cache has the restored committed basis. RSC/Flight
   152	is outside v1.
   153	
   154	## 2. Mechanism inventory — six
   155	
   156	1. **K0 and twin builds.** The closed donor arena is the only DIRECT engine;
   157	   the LOGGED build adds policy at operation boundaries while retaining its
   158	   packed hot layout.
   159	2. **Receipt ledger and exact worlds.** Per-atom tapes, one sequence line,
   160	   stable batch tokens, generation-checked live slots, pass pins, immutable
   161	   per-root lock views, replay folds, retirement, and pin-gated compaction are
   162	   one value-history mechanism.
   163	3. **K1 reach plane.** Real world edges, E-PRESERVE, per-slot reach masks and
   164	   durable touched lists, edge-add carry/delivery, quiescent refresh, and cone
   165	   carry form one reach mechanism beside K0.
   166	4. **World evaluation basis.** The coarse receipt/stage gate, pinned world
   167	   memos, one flattened basis representation, positional lineage capsules,
   168	   and equality revalidation form one cache mechanism.
   169	5. **Value-blind delivery and bindings.** Non-reentrant union walks,
   170	   `walkGen`, watcher/slot render-cycle dedup, synchronous `setState`, mount
   171	   fixup, reconcile checks, and committed-effect drains form one delivery
   172	   mechanism.
   173	6. **Versioned fork/build seam.** Protocol facts F1-F9, stage/publication
   174	   records, action parking, the continuation transform, registrar wrappers,
   175	   retired-token fallback, and `ActionScope.set/dispatch` form one boundary
   176	   mechanism.
   177	
   178	Tracing, schema generation, tests, allocators, epochs, and numeric gates are
   179	process/substrate, not additional concurrency mechanisms.
   180	
   181	### 2.1 Consolidation ledger
   182	
   183	Deleted outright:
   184	
   185	- `WORLD_TAINT` and every set/clear/propagate rule;
   186	- per-node staged-evaluator routing probes;
   187	- `RENDER_NEWEST`, write/stage demotion, and its pass state;
   188	- `fastPathDisabled(pass)`, `lastRetireSeq`, retained retired slots, and the
   189	  saturation force-clear policy;
   190	- per-(root,slot) `lockStamp` and per-atom `lockTerm` scans;
   191	- separate evaluator-stamp vectors and separate Suspense content prefixes;
   192	- a second fn stamp distinct from F9 publication id;
   193	- `ActionScope.runSync`.
   194	
   195	Unified:
   196	
   197	- world-memo validity, evaluator identity, lock-view identity, and Suspense
   198	  content validity consume the same basis;
   199	- a stage record's `stageId` is also its F9 publication id;
   200	- every registrar wrapper and transformed continuation uses the same
   201	  live-token carrier bracket.
   202	
   203	### 2.2 Settled obligations under the simpler invariant
   204	
   205	The design preserves D1-D18's product semantics. Three prior implementation
   206	invariants change representation rather than being ignored:
   207	
   208	- I33's world-leak obligation remains, but its taint implementation is
   209	  deleted. The receipt-count/pin-retention induction in sections 4.5 and 6.1
   210	  covers direct untracked reads and every tracked parent uniformly.
   211	- I34 still has one root-scoped version minted at every lock-in/advance and a
   212	  durable flush. The immutable view's existing id is that version; a second
   213	  per-slot stamp and `lockTerm` are redundant.
   214	- I10/I39 required retired-slot retention or a spill flag because cleared
   215	  reach bits could authorize K0. Reach bits no longer authorize render reads.
   216	  Old tape entries keep `(slot,slotGen)` and `receiptCount` keeps exact-world
   217	  routing closed, so the same forced schedules permit immediate generated-
   218	  slot release. A recycled generation cannot match an old pass.
   219	
   220	Always-log, replay order, K0 closure, clocks, value-blind delivery, lineage
   221	identity, F9 publication, reducer semantics, and the async support boundary
   222	are unchanged.
   223	
   224	## 3. Packed substrate
   225	
   226	K0 starts from the measured arena donor: one interleaved `Int32Array` plane
   227	for node/link records, packed `unknown[]` value/fn side columns, iterative
   228	walks, persistent scratch stacks, and split `link`/`linkInsert` fast paths.
   229	Buffers remain closure constants; growth rebuilds closures only at operation
   230	boundaries. Same-file non-exported `const enum` values provide offsets. K1 is
   231	a separate warm-reused arena so no world bit or branch enters K0 traversal.
   232	
   233	World memos, bases, receipts, basis entries, watcher records, and lock views
   234	use bump/free-list side planes with generation-checked ids. Collections are
   235	built directly with loops and mutation. No steady render constructs a JS
   236	array, `Map`, `Set`, closure, or iterator. Custom equality and sentinel policy
   237	live in wrappers; K0 compares stable references.
   238	
   239	Implementation uses TypeScript `type` declarations, branded integer ids, and
   240	`undefined` for absence. No runtime `null` sentinel is needed. Development
   241	branches use the build-time `__DEV__` define, never a runtime constant.
   242	
   243	The measured donor ratios versus alien-signals v3 are deep 0.90, broad
   244	0.84-0.88, diamond 0.89, reads 0.74-0.87, and create 0.96. Those are inherited
   245	targets, not re-measured claims. [ARENA][SYNTH §18.2] Full-arena
   246	storage, interleaving, closure
   247	constants, and bytecode budgets are retained because the seed measurements
   248	show their alternatives lose materially.
   249	
   250	## 4. Receipt ledger and world arithmetic
   251	
   252	### 4.1 Identities and records
   253	
   254	A **token** is a stable integer batch identity with a deferred bit. It is
   255	never reused while live. A live token occupies one of at most 31 slots and
   256	has a `slotGen`; masks are always interpreted with the captured generation.
   257	Retired tape entries retain `{slot,slotGen}` even after the slot is recycled.
   258	
   259	`globalSeq` is one monotone integer line. Writes, retirements, lock-view ids,
   260	and stage ids mint from it. A pass captures `pin=globalSeq` at start. Each atom

