   261	has a base and a tape of:
   262	
   263	```
   264	{ seq, slot, slotGen, op, retiredSeq }
   265	```
   266	
   267	`op` is `set(value)`, updater, or reducer action. The tape is in `seq` order.
   268	`retiredSeq=0` means live. `receiptCount` counts unswept entries globally; it
   269	is the already required “any live history” fact used by E-PRESERVE and episode
   270	quiescence. It falls only when entries leave tapes, never when their slot
   271	retires. `wc[slot,slotGen]` is the global sequence of that generated token's
   272	latest write, so it is directly comparable with a pass pin.
   273	
   274	### 4.2 Write path
   275	
   276	In LOGGED, a write executes in this order:
   277	
   278	1. F1 returns or lazily mints the writer's token and live slot.
   279	2. Mint `seq`, append the receipt, increment `receiptCount`, and set the slot
   280	   write clock `wc[slot,slotGen]=seq`.
   281	3. Apply the op to K0 NEWEST with stepwise equality. On equal, retain the old
   282	   reference.
   283	4. Run the K0 union K1 reach/delivery walk in the writer's context.
   284	5. Flush core effects only if the outer engine `batch` closes.
   285	
   286	The append precedes the K0 mutation. Thus no callback can observe a changed K0
   287	while `receiptCount==0`.
   288	
   289	An equal write may be dropped only when that atom's tape is empty and the op's
   290	meaning is world-invariant: plain `set`, an updater on an ordinary Atom, or an
   291	action under an immutable constructor reducer. A hook-stageable ReducerAtom
   292	always appends. With nonempty history every op appends, including an equal
   293	`set`.
   294	
   295	### 4.3 Visibility and fold
   296	
   297	A render world is:
   298	
   299	```
   300	{ rootId, included[(slot,slotGen)], pin, lockView, episode, passStages }
   301	```
   302	
   303	Receipt `e` is visible exactly when at least one clause holds:
   304	
   305	1. `e.retiredSeq != 0 && e.retiredSeq <= world.pin`;
   306	2. `(e.slot,e.slotGen)` is included and `e.seq <= world.pin`;
   307	3. the captured lock view contains `(e.slot,e.slotGen,watermark)` and
   308	   `e.seq <= min(world.pin, watermark)`.
   309	
   310	Fold starts at the atom base and visits receipts in increasing `seq`, applying
   311	only visible ops. Equality is applied after every op and retains the old
   312	reference when equal. Updater/reducer callbacks run under a guard that rejects
   313	all signal reads and writes.
   314	
   315	**Replay invariant.** Base case: before any receipt, fold equals the base and
   316	React's queue has the same base. Inductive step: for the next receipt, both
   317	models either skip it because its batch is excluded or apply the same op to
   318	the same accumulator; stepwise equality preserves the same representative.
   319	Retirement changes visibility, not order. Therefore every prefix has the same
   320	value as React's lane-filtered updater queue.
   321	
   322	### 4.4 Immutable root lock views
   323	
   324	Each root points to an immutable sorted vector of
   325	`{slot,slotGen,watermark}` and an id minted from `globalSeq`. A root commit
   326	raises each included token's watermark to the committing pass pin and swaps a
   327	new pooled view if any entry changed. Dropping a retired token also re-mints.
   328	The committing pass is the only same-root pass allowed to survive that swap;
   329	F2 ends/discards other resumable passes first. Old vectors remain until their
   330	last captured reference drops.
   331	
   332	`lockViewId` is the only lock visibility version. It is in world keys and the
   333	common basis header. A lock change forces committed effects reached through
   334	the changed slot's durable touched list. No atom fingerprint scans a view.
   335	
   336	### 4.5 Retirement, slot release, and compaction
   337	
   338	Retirement occurs once per token, whether or not React committed work.
   339	`committed=false` does not discard writes. In order:
   340	
   341	1. Mint one retirement sequence and write it to every receipt of the token.
   342	   Mint `retireVisStamp` on each touched atom.
   343	2. Publish any root lock-view removals only after those stamps exist.
   344	3. Force committed-effect/reconcile drains by enumerating the token's durable
   345	   touched list; the write-time queue is only an optimization.
   346	4. Clear this slot's reach bits and watcher dedup through that same list, then
   347	   release the slot and increment `slotGen`.
   348	5. Compact only the all-retired tape prefix whose every `retiredSeq` is at or
   349	   below the minimum live pass pin. Decrement `receiptCount` for removed
   350	   entries and preserve replay order in the base.
   351	
   352	Retired entries can therefore outlive their slot, but generation checks keep
   353	old masks distinct from a recycled occupant. Since only live tokens own
   354	slots, the 31-live-token premise is the complete capacity bound; there is no
   355	saturation state.
   356	
   357	**Pin-retention invariant.** Base: a new pass pins before later retirements.
   358	Step: an entry whose retirement is later than that pin fails the compaction
   359	predicate, so `receiptCount>0` and the entry remains foldable. Only after the
   360	last excluding pin ends may compaction remove it, at which point no pass can
   361	ask for the older world. This is the construction that permits immediate
   362	slot release without a spill flag.
   363	
   364	## 5. K1 reach and delivery
   365	
   366	K1 records the real dependency edges discovered by exact-world evaluations.
   367	It is a union across worlds and may contain cycles even though every single
   368	world evaluation is cycle-free. Edges are add-only within an episode.
   369	
   370	For a write in slot `s`, a full walk over K0 union K1:
   371	
   372	- stamps each visited record with the current `walkGen`;
   373	- ORs `(s,slotGen)` into each node's reach mask and appends the node once to
   374	  `touchedList[s,slotGen]`;
   375	- calls each reached watcher at most once for `(watcher,s,slotGen,renderCycle)`;
   376	- follows every outgoing edge regardless of dirty/equality state.
   377	
   378	The watcher call is `setState` in the writer's stack. Marks never stop the
   379	walk. A watcher re-arms its slot bit when it renders, so a later write after a
   380	completed render can deliver again.
   381	
   382	When a K1 edge is added, existing reach bits propagate through existing
   383	out-edges to a fixed point. For every newly carried still-live token, watcher
   384	delivery runs in `runInBatch(token)`. Edge additions discovered in a render
   385	slice drain at yield/end. Edge additions discovered while a full walk has
   386	`walkDepth=1` join that same drain and run after the walk. Core effects flush
   387	after it. Full walks contain no reducer, equality, computed, effect, or other
   388	user callback; React's state enqueue does not synchronously render. Hence
   389	`walkDepth` never exceeds one.
   390	
   391	**Walk termination.** Base: the start record is stamped with generation G.
   392	Step: an unstamped record is stamped once before its finite outgoing edges are
   393	pushed; a stamped record pushes nothing. With no nested full walk, no other G
   394	can overwrite a stamp until completion. The finite union graph is therefore
   395	visited at most once per record, including when it contains a cycle.
   396	
   397	**E-PRESERVE.** While `receiptCount>0`, every edge removed by a K0 retrack is
   398	copied to K1 with endpoint generations. This is not slot-scoped. If no receipt
   399	exists, a removed branch cannot matter to another world; a later receipt on
   400	the branch selector creates history before K0 mutates and its evaluation
   401	records the needed world path.
   402	
   403	At true quiescence—`receiptCount==0`, no live pass, no unpublished stage, and
   404	no active delivery—refresh every K1-touched node with a committed watcher or
   405	effect snapshot through K0 NEWEST, then reset K1 and bump the episode. A
   406	target that writes during refresh retries once. On a second failure it is
   407	exempt and its full reverse-reachable K1 cone is carried to the next episode.
   408	For a fixed observed set, the rank
   409	`sum(2 - failures[target])` decreases on every failed refresh, so the sweep
   410	terminates in at most `2N+1` attempts; ordinary signal-loop limits cover an
   411	unbounded stream of newly observed targets.
   412	
   413	## 6. Exact-world evaluation and the common basis
   414	
   415	### 6.1 The only render read gate
   416	
   417	Every active render slice has a pass frame supplied by F2. A signal read in
   418	that slice executes:
   419	
   420	```
   421	if receiptCount == 0 && passStages is empty:
   422	  return K0.read(node)
   423	return readInWorld(node, pass.world)
   424	```
   425	
   426	There is no node-local reach, taint, cleanliness, newest, or spillover
   427	conjunct. During a yield the pass frame is absent, so handlers and core effects
   428	read K0 NEWEST.
   429	
   430	**World-isolation invariant.** Base: with no receipts and no stages, every
   431	world equals K0. Step for a write: the append makes `receiptCount>0` before K0
   432	changes, so all subsequent render reads fold. Step for retirement: an
   433	excluding live pin retains the receipt and count; without such a pin the
   434	retired value is committed for every possible pass. Step for a stage: the
   435	pass table becomes nonempty before the staged evaluator is read. Step for
   436	discard/promotion: the stage table dies or becomes committed, and F2 prevents
   437	a same-root stale pass from resuming across publication. Thus a K0 render
   438	serve occurs only when its world and evaluator basis are identical.
   439	
   440	This proof covers tracked parents of untracked children without propagation:
   441	when an untracked K0 read could embed a receipted value, `receiptCount>0`, so
   442	neither that child nor any tracked parent can be served from K0 to a render.
   443	
   444	### 6.2 World memos
   445	
   446	Atoms fold directly. A computed is memoized by `(nodeGen, worldKey)`, where
   447	the key contains episode, root, included slot generations, pin, and
   448	`lockViewId`. A pass pins the exact memo record it uses; another pass may
   449	create another record but never overwrite it. `EVALUATING` in the same world
   450	throws a cycle. Evaluation rejects writes, tracks ordinary reads into K1, and
   451	folds untracked reads in the same world without adding an edge or a basis
   452	dependency.
   453	
   454	Fresh nodes take this path whenever history or stages exist, so their first
   455	evaluation cannot leak K0.
   456	
   457	### 6.3 One canonical basis
   458	
   459	A basis is a flat packed sequence built directly during evaluation:
   460	
   461	- header: episode, world identity, `lockViewId`;
   462	- one `(slot,slotGen,wc)` for each included/locked live slot;
   463	- tracked atom `(atomId,nodeGen,fingerprint,valueRef)` entries;
   464	- computed `(nodeId,nodeGen,effectiveStageId,valueRef)` entries for completed
   465	  nested reads, flattened through those reads;
   466	- the resource-owning computed's effective stage id in the header;
   467	- thenable `(capsuleGen,settlementVersion)` entries.
   468	
   469	`fingerprint` is the atom's newest world-visible receipt seq, base seq,
   470	reducer stage id, and `retireVisStamp`. Lock visibility is represented once by
   471	the header, not per atom.
   472	
   473	Validation first compares generations, episode, world identity, stage ids,
   474	and slot clocks. If every cheap fact matches, it serves. On a moved atom fact,
   475	it folds that atom in the candidate world and applies the atom's equality; on
   476	equal it retains `valueRef` and restamps. On a moved nested-computed stage id,
   477	it evaluates that completed child under the effective stage and compares its
   478	stable output reference; on equal it restamps. A changed value invalidates the
   479	consumer. The resource-owning evaluator has no completed output at its
   480	`ctx.use` position, so its stage-id change invalidates the capsule directly:
   481	the factory code itself may have changed. Settlement changes invalidate the
   482	throwing/suspending sentinel.
   483	
   484	This single representation is consumed by world memos, `ctx.previous`
   485	records, effect snapshots, and Suspense capsules. Consumers may stop at the
   486	first changed value, but they do not maintain translated copies.
   487	
   488	### 6.4 Suspense capsules
   489	
   490	The fork supplies a render lineage id stable across retries/replays for one
   491	root and logical batch set. `ctx.use(factory)` owns a capsule at
   492	`(nodeGen,lineageId,position)`. The capsule stores its settled/pending thenable
   493	and the common basis prefix at that position.
   494	
   495	On retry, equal basis values reuse the identical thenable. A moved header,
   496	clock, fingerprint, or nested stage id runs the value revalidation above.
   497	Equal values restamp the capsule in place; a changed value or owning-stage id
   498	generation-drops this position and later positions, then calls the factory
   499	again. The eager `ctx.use(thenable)` form can guarantee identity only when the
   500	caller supplies the same thenable.
   501	
   502	For a pass containing several batches, identity is lineage, while content is
   503	the full world basis. A token alone, a mask alone, and a pass serial are never
   504	keys.
   505	
   506	### 6.5 Previous values
   507	
   508	K0 NEWEST uses the donor's previous value. A world evaluation uses the prior
   509	value of the exact pinned memo record. A fresh world record uses a K0 value
   510	only when the render gate would allow K0; otherwise `ctx.previous` is
   511	`undefined`. Errors and suspension boxes count as values for this rule.
   512	
   513	## 7. Delivery, subscriptions, and effects
   514	
   515	### 7.1 Watchers
   516	
   517	A watcher is a mounted component record containing its root, node, last
   518	rendered value, render world, render pin, and a 31-bit delivery mask paired
   519	with slot generations. Delivery synchronously increments a private React
   520	state cell. Calling it in the writer's execution context gives the update the

