 succeeded in 0ms:
   521	writer's priority and token. No implicit notification batch exists.
   522	
   523	Delivery is value-blind. Equality still cuts off K0 and world recomputation,
   524	but it does not decide whether already-finished React work is safe. The
   525	per-(watcher,slot,render-cycle) bit only deduplicates work already scheduled in
   526	that same token; rendering clears that token's bit.
   527	
   528	At fold/reconcile time, the binding compares the watcher's last rendered
   529	value against the value in the committing root world. An equal value retains
   530	the reference and needs no new React update. This reconcile comparison never
   531	suppresses the original write-time delivery.
   532	
   533	### 7.2 Mount and subscribe fixup
   534	
   535	The layout-phase subscription records the rendered value/world first, then:
   536	
   537	```
   538	for each live written token t whose generated slot is in reachMask(node):
   539	  if renderWorld includes t && wc[t] <= renderPin:
   540	    continue
   541	  if runInBatch(t, () => setState(watcher)) == RETIRED:
   542	    setState(watcher) // urgent pre-paint fallback
   543	
   544	now = evaluate(node, committedForRoot(root))
   545	if !node.isEqual(now, renderedValue):
   546	  setState(watcher)   // urgent pre-paint correction
   547	```
   548	
   549	The skip applies only to the token-lane correction. The committed comparison
   550	is unconditional. Layout cannot run for an uncommitted mount; F3 installs the
   551	root lock view before layout, so a mount from its own committing pass compares
   552	against a world containing the prefix it rendered. A token that retired
   553	before the loop is caught by the comparison. A token retiring between the
   554	test and `runInBatch` returns `RETIRED` and takes the fallback.
   555	
   556	### 7.3 Late edges and reconcile backstop
   557	
   558	A K1 edge created after a write carries every still-live reach bit and queues
   559	the corresponding `runInBatch` deliveries before that render pass can commit.
   560	The fork also invokes a pre-mutation reconcile check for a root: every watcher
   561	rendered by the candidate commit is compared to the pass world it claims. A
   562	late update inserted after completed work makes React restart that work; it is
   563	not allowed to commit and repair a torn frame later.
   564	
   565	### 7.4 Effects and observed lifecycle
   566	
   567	`useSignalEffect` records a common basis snapshot of its committed-for-root
   568	reads. It is considered for re-run at:
   569	
   570	- a root commit containing a reached token;
   571	- every lock-view lock-in or watermark advance, by the changed token's
   572	  durable touched list;
   573	- token retirement, by the retiring token's durable touched list;
   574	- thenable settlement.
   575	
   576	Lock-view drains force basis revalidation even though no per-atom lock stamp
   577	exists. Cleanup runs before the next committed invocation. A deps change uses
   578	React's own effect cleanup/re-fire and retracks from scratch.
   579	
   580	Core `effect()` uses K0 NEWEST, is queued by the ordinary graph, and flushes at
   581	the configured engine batch boundary. Atom observed-lifecycle counts include
   582	watchers and effects; microtask damping makes StrictMode mount/unmount flaps
   583	net to one start and one eventual cleanup.
   584	
   585	## 8. Hook evaluator identity and F9 publication
   586	
   587	### 8.1 Immutable evaluator records
   588	
   589	Each hook-stageable node has an immutable committed evaluator record
   590	`{fn,depsValues,stageId,ownerRoot,ownerHookGen}`. A pass invocation selects in
   591	this order:
   592	
   593	1. if incoming deps equal the committed record, use that record;
   594	2. else if they equal this lineage's current record for the hook, reuse it;
   595	3. else create a record whose `stageId=++globalSeq` and replace the lineage's
   596	   current pointer, retaining the old record while any pass/capsule holds it.
   597	
   598	Equal deps use the record's old function, matching `useMemo`. `stageId` is
   599	also the opaque F9 publication id; there is no second fn stamp. A pass that
   600	selects a noncommitted record puts it in `passStages` before any read of the
   601	node, forcing all later render reads through exact-world evaluation.
   602	
   603	If deps oscillate A-to-B-to-A within one lineage, committed A is reused when
   604	available. An uncommitted A that was displaced may receive a new id; that is a
   605	real evaluator transition, but the common basis retains a resource when its
   606	re-evaluated output is equal. An unpublished record is never reused by another
   607	lineage. Once F9 promotes it, it is the committed record and all later
   608	lineages may select it.
   609	
   610	### 8.2 Publication
   611	
   612	Render attaches the stage id plus `(nodeGen,ownerRoot,hookSlot,workGen)` to
   613	the exact WIP hook. F9 emits only records whose hooks become current. Hidden
   614	Offscreen hooks count as current; error-abandoned children and stale
   615	alternates do not. A generation CAS rejects an obsolete publication.
   616	
   617	For one commit the order is:
   618	
   619	1. publish winning evaluator/reducer records;
   620	2. dirty each published K0 node and run its value-blind delivery walk in the
   621	   committing batch context;
   622	3. for a promoted ReducerAtom with pending receipts, replay those receipts
   623	   from its committed base under the new reducer and install the equality-
   624	   stable K0 NEWEST result;
   625	4. install the root's new lock view;
   626	5. perform retirements/folds due at this commit;
   627	6. run reconcile checks, then user layout effects.
   628	
   629	The publication walk is required even when the current value compares equal:
   630	the new evaluator can change a downstream result on its next inputs. Reducer
   631	re-fold precedes the walk's reconcile read.
   632	
   633	`publicationsComplete(passId)` releases that pass's hook attachments. Pass
   634	discard releases pass refs but not the lineage cache: retries in the same
   635	lineage must retain its current immutable record. F5 lineage death releases
   636	unpublished lineage records and capsules; published records are committed
   637	ownership.
   638	
   639	### 8.3 Reducer rules
   640	
   641	Constructor ReducerAtoms have immutable reducers and use ordinary receipt
   642	drop rules. Hook ReducerAtoms always append actions. A pass folds with its
   643	selected reducer record; committed/core NEWEST uses the committed record.
   644	Promotion reinterprets pending actions, never actions already compacted into
   645	the committed base. Publication precedes same-commit retirement, so both use
   646	the reducer that produced the committed tree.
   647	
   648	The single-owner-root check in section 1.3 is performed when a watcher first
   649	subscribes. It is unnecessary for immutable constructor reducers and ordinary
   650	computeds.
   651	
   652	## 9. Async actions and carrier boundaries
   653	
   654	Parking and attribution are separate. F3 keeps an action token live until the
   655	thenable returned from the transition action settles. The carrier tells F1
   656	which live token owns a post-await write.
   657	
   658	Carrier ladder:
   659	
   660	1. native AsyncContext, when the host provides the required semantics;
   661	2. the measured twin-build transform [I30/SP-F8]: compiled async bodies dispatch through
   662	   a token-carrying generator only while an action is armed;
   663	3. Node AsyncLocalStorage by explicit server opt-in only;
   664	4. otherwise registration fails its loud asynchronous boot probe.
   665	
   666	At rung 2, wrappers are installed on the 0-to-1 armed-action transition and
   667	removed on 1-to-0 if they still own the host property. They cover callback
   668	registration for `setTimeout`, `setInterval`, `queueMicrotask`,
   669	`requestAnimationFrame`, `requestIdleCallback`, and same-realm
   670	`MessagePort.addEventListener('message', cb)`/`onmessage` assignment. Each
   671	captures the current token at registration and invokes through:
   672	
   673	```
   674	if token is still live-and-parked: push token; call; finally restore
   675	else: call under ambient context; dev-warn once for this registration
   676	```
   677	
   678	An async callback invoked inside the bracket instantiates its transformed
   679	body while the token is current. A nested registration captures the same
   680	token. Every interval tick repeats the liveness test. A pre-existing
   681	MessagePort listener triggered by `postMessage` inside an action is not a
   682	registration inside the action and belongs to the documented opaque-boundary
   683	class; use `scope.set/dispatch` in that listener. Cross-realm ports cannot
   684	carry tokens.
   685	
   686	If a transformed continuation itself resumes after settlement, its push uses
   687	the same liveness check and falls back to ambient classification. It never
   688	re-interns a retired token or extends parking for an un-awaited child.
   689	
   690	`ActionScope.set(atom,value)` and `ActionScope.dispatch(atom,action)` supply
   691	the captured token explicitly after checking realm, generation, and
   692	liveness. Calls after settlement throw “ActionScope closed.” Raw post-await
   693	writes in untransformed code are attributed to their ambient batch, are never
   694	lost, and warn while another action is armed. The support matrix says to
   695	transform that code, use ActionScope, or use an AsyncContext host.
   696	
   697	## 10. Fork protocol v4
   698	
   699	The boundary carries only opaque integer ids, generated token tuples, and
   700	callbacks. No Fiber, lane mask, or React update-queue object crosses it.
   701	There are nine facts and **16 seam touch points**.
   702	
   703	### 10.1 Facts
   704	
   705	**F1 — write context.** `currentBatch()` returns `{token,deferred,realm}` or
   706	ambient. It lazily claims a token for store-only work. A carried token is
   707	returned only while live-and-parked.
   708	
   709	**F2 — render pass lifecycle.** Start supplies
   710	`{passId,rootId,includedTokens,lineageId}` and the binding captures
   711	`pin=globalSeq` in the resulting frame. Yield removes the render frame; resume
   712	restores it; end declares complete or discarded. Before F9 publishes a new
   713	evaluator basis or F3 changes a root lock view, every other resumable pass on
   714	that root receives discard.
   715	
   716	**F3 — root commit and retirement.** Root commit supplies the exact included
   717	token watermarks. A token retires exactly once after all root work and its
   718	returned async action settle. `committed=false` is diagnostic only and does
   719	not change persistence. F9 publication and lock-in/retirement ordering follow
   720	section 8.2.
   721	
   722	**F4 — lane-scoped scheduling.** `runInBatch(token,callback)` executes the
   723	callback so React queues its updates in that live token and returns `JOINED`;
   724	if retirement won the race it does not run the callback and returns
   725	`RETIRED`.
   726	
   727	**F5 — render lineage.** A lineage id is stable across retries/replays of one
   728	root and logical batch set and dies at commit or abandonment. It is not a pass
   729	serial or token-set hash.
   730	
   731	**F6 — DOM mutation window.** One edge reports entry/exit so tracing and the
   732	reconcile backstop can distinguish pre-mutation correction from user layout.
   733	
   734	**F7 — root identity.** Every pass and commit carries a stable root id; ids
   735	are generation-checked and never reused live. Portals report the parent root.
   736	
   737	**F8 — action parking and capabilities.** Park/settle edges expose the token
   738	lifetime. Protocol registration reports carrier and registrar-wrapper
   739	capabilities so the binding can run its per-bundle boot probe.
   740	
   741	**F9 — hook publication.** Render attaches an opaque stage id to one WIP hook;
   742	commit emits winning ids before root lock/fold/layout and completes the pass's
   743	publication set.
   744	
   745	### 10.2 The 16 touch points
   746	
   747	1. protocol registration/capability negotiation;
   748	2. current-batch classification and lazy claim;
   749	3. pass start;
   750	4. pass yield;
   751	5. pass resume;
   752	6. pass end/discard;
   753	7. lineage death;
   754	8. root commit/lock watermark publication;
   755	9. exactly-once token retirement;
   756	10. `runInBatch` override scope;
   757	11. DOM mutation-window edge (one paired site);
   758	12. action park;
   759	13. action settle;
   760	14. WIP-hook publication attachment;
   761	15. winning-hook publication emission;
   762	16. publication-complete sweep.
   763	
   764	### 10.3 Fork invariants
   765	
   766	- A live token maps to one lane/batch identity; its integer stays stable while
   767	  React may recycle internal lane bits.
   768	- A pass's included tokens and pin never mutate. Yield/resume changes only
   769	  call-stack activity.
   770	- Same-root evaluator publication and lock changes first discard other
   771	  resumable passes; a discarded pass cannot emit F9 or commit.
   772	- F9 emission, root lock publication, retirement folds, reconcile, and layout
   773	  occur in that order.
   774	- Retirement is exactly once and waits for async parking independently of
   775	  subscriber count.
   776	- `runInBatch` either joins the exact live token or reports retirement; it
   777	  never silently creates a replacement transition.
   778	
