     1	# Fork charter (frozen seed)
     2	
     3	The old constraint — "minimal additive patch to React" — is **lifted**. We
     4	own the fork. Depth is allowed; what is scored is size, maintainability, and
     5	seam stability, not shallowness for its own sake.
     6	
     7	## Goals, restated as scoreable properties
     8	
     9	1. **Fork size**: count of touched reconciler files and lines; count of new
    10	   concepts introduced into reconciler code.
    11	2. **Maintainability**: every hook site edge-triggered from a place the
    12	   reconciler already mutates its own bookkeeping (never sampled state);
    13	   each site documents its invariant in place; the fork carries its own
    14	   reconciler-level test suite that runs on every rebase; inert-when-unused
    15	   (one null-check per site with no listener).
    16	3. **Seam stability** (the co-design goal): the signals library depends only
    17	   on a versioned protocol document (`fork-protocol.md` in the design), not
    18	   on reconciler internals. Judge runs a **rebase drill**: "React renamed
    19	   lanes / moved commit phases / changed update-queue internals — what in
    20	   the signals library changes?" The right answer is "nothing; the fork
    21	   re-implements the same protocol facts."
    22	
    23	## Protocol facts known to be required (from the acceptance battery)
    24	
    25	- Write classification: is-a-write-right-now deferred; which batch (integer
    26	  token, minted lazily, never reused live; deferred bit in the token).
    27	- Pass lifecycle: start(root, includedBatches) / end — **plus yield/resume
    28	  edges** (C7: handlers run in yield gaps; wall-clock pass scoping is wrong).
    29	- Retirement: exactly once per token, with committed flag; per-root commit
    30	  lock-in for spanning batches (C11); async-action parking (C12).
    31	- Lane-scoped scheduling: run a callback so its updates join an existing
    32	  batch's lanes (`runInBatch`-class; C6, C10).
    33	- A stable render-lineage identity for suspense caches across a batch's
    34	  passes (C15).
    35	- DOM mutation window (unrelated nicety; keep).
    36	
    37	Candidates may propose MORE than this list — that is the point of the
    38	charter — but every addition must earn its place against goals 1–3.
    39	
    40	## The liberated design space (directions candidates may now take seriously)
    41	
    42	- **Deeper observation**: expose the include-set/lineage/yield facts above
    43	  natively rather than reconstructing them.
    44	- **Lane-scoped execution**: richer entanglement/override scopes than a
    45	  single `runInBatch`.
    46	- **React-owned external state** (the wildcard): fiber-detached update
    47	  queues managed by the reconciler itself — atoms whose visibility/rebase
    48	  semantics are literally React's own update-queue code, deleting the
    49	  library's reimplementation of lane filtering and rebasing. If a candidate
    50	  takes this route it must confront honestly: hook queues are per-fiber and
    51	  single-consumer (an atom is many-consumer — closer to context than to a
    52	  hook); non-React reads/effects need a synchronous fold path anyway;
    53	  reconciler surgery at this depth makes rebase cost the dominant risk, so
    54	  goal 2 is the make-or-break axis. License to fail fast: a candidate may
    55	  conclude "explored, not viable, because X" — that conclusion, with the
    56	  schedule/mechanism that kills it, is a valuable round output.
    57	
    58	## Hard rules
    59	
    60	- No Fiber objects, no lane bitmasks, no update-queue internals cross the
    61	  boundary — integers and documented callbacks only.
    62	- Version-skew: bindings feature-detect the protocol and fail loudly on
    63	  stock React (no silent degraded mode).
    64	- The fork's test suite is part of the design deliverable, not an
    65	  afterthought: every protocol fact gets a reconciler-level test.

